@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

@node undo "Undoing of accidentally deleted lines, part of lines and words"

Every  text-editor  offers  a  function to undo steps which previously have been applied to the text lying in the
editor's environment - now also BareED offers this.

As  you might already guess, BareED's UNDO-function is unusual compared to any other text-editor's UNDO
mechanism (since BareED is different, too ;).

Normally,  any  text-editor  recognizes and remembers every step you make (moving cursor, enter and delete
characters  and  so  on)  and  applies  the  last  remembered when you do "UNDO". Then, this UNDO-step is
removed from the list of UNDOs.

So,  if  you  going  to UNDO a step that you made for example a 1/2 hour earlier and you added and removed
since  that  lines,  you  have  to go back through all steps the text-editor has remembered until you reach the
one you are looking for. This is quiet a hassle that the most people are not willingly to do.
Since I don't like that behaviour too, I thought of a better solution.

1st	The most (99.9 %) of all mistakes are done by accidentally deleting a line using the keyboard.
2nd	It's  in  my  mind  not  necessary  to  remember  insertion  and  deletion of single characters since I
	believe the user knows what he does (almost).
3rd	Modifications  from  the  outside  don't  need  to  be  remembered  since  they will be applied to an
	(almost) already existing file which was already backed up.

So,  BareED  will  only  do  a  minimum  of  what other text-editors do when they undo changes. But applying
UNDO  without  remembering  any  action  between  deletion  and  insertion  gives  a  problem.  To which line
belongs  the  UNDO-contents  when  several  lines  have  been  displaced  since  the remembering? Luckily
BareED already supported back-tracking for bookmarks which was extended for UNDO line back-tracking.

BareED  remembers only deleted lines, partly deleted lines, inserted lines and deleted words and rememebers
only  the  last  10 delete actions. This should be enough since only the relevant deletions will be remembered
and not the irrelevant moving of the cursor, displacing lines, entering new characters and lines.

NOTE:	In  case  the  line  to  which  the  UNDO-level  is  assigned  does  not  exist anymore, a requester
	appears  telling so and asking you to insert the contents at the current position. This mostly occurrs
	when you delete at the end of the archive from down to top lines. It's also possible that the line with
	the  initial  contents  does not anymore exists - in this case you should be carefully - perhaps you
	should only remove this item - since it could be obsolete!

@endnode

@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

@node context "Context menu"

The context menu will expand and simplify the functionality of the standard menu for common actions.
For example cutting, copying or pasting texts is now really easy to perform using this context menu.
Also, it can be used to terminate all running DAC applications who support it (e.g. text highlighters).
If  you  need indentation of texts (either the expansion or reduction), it is also really easy to perform now using
the context menu.


The context menu will show only up in case the mouse pointer resides within the drawing area of BareED.

In  case  you  want  for  example the main window menus to appear, using a pop-up patch like MagicMenus,
press  some key (for example the shift key) once or hold it, and don't move the mouse until you press the right
mouse button in order to let the pop-up patch show the normal menus.

After  leaving  this  normal  menu  a mouse movement is necessary in order to let the context menu of BareED
take place instead of the normal menus.

An  other  method  in order to display the main window menus, can be achieved by moving the mouse pointer
to screen's top or at least to BareED's window frame and pressing there the right mouse button.

Remember:  Any  mouse  movement  within  BareED's  drawing  area  tells BareED to refer from now on to the
	  context menu and not to the main window menus.

Although  many  aspects of this context menu can be changed (colours, transparency, spacings, texts and so
on)  there  is  currently no chance for you to change it. I'm sorry for this inconvenience - but actually BareED
is only at a beta stage of development and some essential things like the preference editor are missing.


In  case  you  don't  need  the context menu you can disable it by specifying @{b}"DISABLE=CONTEXTMENU"@{ub} in
BareED's icon.

If you disabled also the wheel movement option, then the string must look like this in our example:
@{b}"DISABLE=WHEELMOVEMENT|CONTEXTMENU"@{ub}

There  is a work-around in BareED in order to make the separator character ("|") useable, because under OS
3.0 it is broken.

If   you   only   want  the  context-menu  to  be  shown  when  a  block  of  text  is  marked,  set  DISABLE  to
ALWAYSPOPUP, which gives in our example:
@{b}"DISABLE=WHEELMOVEMENT|ALWAYSPOPUP"@{ub}

@endnode

@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

@node history "History menu"

History menu

The label "History" gets used by me as abbreviation instead of "recently edited files".

The  History  menu  hid  when  you  start BareED for the first time. As soon as you start saving files to disk, or
load them, the History menu will appear if BareED has at least remembered two files you recently edited.

Selecting the menu item for a remembered file will instruct BareED to do two things:
- loading the file in question
  and
- changing the path for the ASL file requester, which is responsible for loading files, to this location.

The  History menu is dynamically updated by BareED whenever you save and load files. The last one you've
saved  to  disk  or  loaded  from  disk is displayed at the top of the menu. In addition, the less time has passed
between  the present session and the last visit of the file, the more the file's position will move to the top within
the menu.

Because  there is a limitation for the amount for recently loaded or saved files, BareED throws away the eldest
when  a  new  one  is  loaded  or  saved  to  disk and the amount of entries has exhausted a certain capacity
(currently 20 files).

In  case  you  want  to  get  rid of the currently shown History list, use the menu item "Clear History". Then, all
items except that one representing the currently edited document will be cleared - even on disk!
In  case  you  only  want  to  clear  a single item, hold down the CTRL key and choose the item of the History
menu you want to have cleared.


The History feature of BareED is also good for another thing:
- The  path  to  the  last  saved  or loaded file is used as initial path for the ASL file requester upon launching
BareED - in case the path is present, otherwise the default (BareED's) gets used.

@endnode

@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

@node settings "Settings and preferences"


Settings and preferences
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ

When  "Create  Icons?" is enabled BareED writes along with the archive the settings you have chosen for this
archive, for example the colours, window position and so on.

BareED  offers  no  possibility  to  choose  the  global  preferences  with  some exceptions: You can enter into
BareED's  icon  the  monitor  type  you  wish  the  Asl-requester-module to display - and whether you like to
reserve  the  pens taken for the "knob-bank", so that other application won't be able to use these pens and no
false colours occur. In addition, you can tell BareED whether you like to start with the button interface enabled
and some things more...

All these characteristics are entered normally through the use of the tool-types in BareED's icon!

@{b}MONITORTYPE=ALL|FOREIGN|LIKEWB|NATIVE@{ub}

Where

	@{b}ALL@{ub}	...  to display each monitor who is available on your machine

	@{b}FOREIGN@{ub} ...  only  display  non-Amiga  modes, i.e. you must have already plugged into
			    a Z3 bus a 3rd party graphic device (for example)

	@{b}LIKEWB@{ub}	... allows   only   to  display  such  modes  which  will  be  supported  by  the
			   Workbench,  i.e.  no  HAM,  EHB,  DPF,  15  bit  and  modes with an alpha
			   channel

	@{b}NATIVE@{ub}	...  to  display only those monitors that can be directly displayed by the Amiga
			    hardware

Combinations of the above stated are allowed, such as

	@{b}MONITORTYPE=FOREIGN|LIKEWB@{ub}	(e.g. for the Draco/Pegasos computer)

		Or

	@{b}MONITORTYPE=NATIVE|ALL@{ub}

Please do not combine @{b}NATIVE@{ub} and @{b}FOREIGN@{ub}....


@{b}KNOBPENS=RESERVE@{ub}

	...  instructs  BareED  to  reserve  the  pens  taken  for the knob-bank - in order to avoid each time
	re-mapping  the  colours  for  a  newly  generated  surrounding  in  case  other  applications have
	successfully  attempted  to reserve pens for their own purpose, e.g. image viewers (like MultiView),
	Workbench games, icon patches (NewIcons) or OS 3.5 icon subsystem.


@{b}BUTTONS=YES@{ub}

	... instructs BareED to turn on and to display the button groin upon start


@{b}NOICONSAVE=YES@{ub}

	...  normally,  BareED  will by default create an icon for any project-file which is going to be saved
	to  disk.  When  this  tool-type  is  set,  no  icon will be saved along with the project-file - and the
	checkmark is removed from "Create Icons?".


@{b}NORELOADFONT=YES@{ub}

	...  by  default  BareED  tries  to  display  the  font  described through the project-file icon. With this
	tool-type  you  can  suppress  it,  then  only  your  chosen  font  will be used, regardless what the
	project-file was originally edited with.


@{b}PRIORITY=0@{ub}

	...  by  default  BareED runs at a task-priority of zero, with this tool-type you can change BareED's
	task-priority in range from minus one ("-1") to plus 4 ("4").
	This  is maybe useful in case you run next BareED a BareED plug-in and also any software which
	needs  much  CPU  time  (for  example  a  MP3 player). In case you increased the task-priority the
	plug-in's task-priority will also increase - which in terms can result in a much better performance.


@{b}STDEXIT@{ub}

	...  by  default BareED closes the opened Screen and Window first and then it will prompt for asking
	if  you  would  like to back-up the changed file. In case this tool-type is set, it shows a dialog-box
	where  you  can  decide if you wish to quit BareED at all, or to back-up the archive with or without
	quitting BareED.

	Once more:
	By  means  of this feature a standardized (more or less) exit routine is used by BareED in which the
	screen and window remain open.

	You have four possibilities here:

		@{b}Save@{ub}
	Back-up the archive only, without quitting BareED.

		@{b}Save and Exit@{ub}
	Back-up the archive and then quit BareED.

		@{b}Abandon@{ub}
	The archive is rejected (nirvana) and BareED is forced to quit. Warning: Data loss!
	As last possibility for a changed archive one safety query is prompted later again!

		@{b}Cancel@{ub}
	Doesn't exits BareED and doesn't saves the archive!


@{b}SMOOTHSCROLL@{ub}

	By  the  default  this is disabled. Specifying it causes BareED to scroll a line of text multiple times -
	in order to avoid stumbling texts - when scrolled.

	Optional you can specify the amount of division that BareED should use to scroll one line of text.

		@{b}SMOOTHSCROLL=1@{ub}	Scroll every line of text  @{fg highlight}(Caution: slowest)@{fg text}
		@{b}SMOOTHSCROLL=3@{ub}	Scroll every n/3 line of text
		@{b}SMOOTHSCROLL=7@{ub}	Scroll every n/7 line of text
	where 'n' is the height of the font plus one.

	No value lower than 4 is recommended  - exception: you have a really fast machine!

	NOTE:	Smooth  scrolling is only performed when BareED's window is the frontmost or if you use
		the menu-item "System Refresh".
		Use smooth scrolling with care since it was reported that it is damn slow.

	If  your  key-repeat  speed  value  (@{fg highlight}@{" SYS:Prefs/Input " SYSTEM "run SYS:Prefs/Input"}@{fg text}) is settled above of 0.04 seconds (e.g. 0.05,
	0.06  a.s.o) then BareED will be disturbed by this timeout value - and it isn't possible for BareED to
	smoothly scroll...
	The key-repeat delay value has got no influence on BareED's smooth scroll...

@{b}SCROLLTIMEOUT@{ub}

	The  scroll  timeout-values  for  the  page,  line,  image,  scroller  are now always accumulated by
	BareED - taken into account the user's key-repead speed.
	There  is no more necessity to set via @{fg highlight}@{" SYS:Prefs/Input " SYSTEM "run SYS:Prefs/Input"}@{fg text} the key-repeat speed to something below
	0.05 second. Even greater values may work!

	--- OBSOLETE ---
	SCROLLTIMEOUT is a value which will be used in case @{b}SMOOTHSCROLL@{ub} is used.
	It  says  nothing  more  than  that after a scroll process has been invoked a short timeout is taken to
	avoid fierce jumping texts.
	Normally,  this  time  is fixed to 4000 milli-seconds. Since that value may not avoid those stumbling
	texts, you can choose your own value that fits to your machine.
	If  you  would  like  to dynamically adjust this value - which I suggest - you can enter instead of a
	value  the  keyword  @{b}AUTO@{ub} - then BareED makes some tests (upon start) and decides what timeout
	values to use.


@{b}DISABLE=WHEELMOVEMENT|CONTEXTMENU|ALWAYSPOPUP@{ub}
               @{b}VERYLASTCHANCESAVE|PAGEMOVEMENT|SINGLESIGNDELETION|ENVACCESS@{ub}

	Introducing  the  DISABLE  keyword  allows to disable some features of BareED which normally are
	enabled.

		@{b}WHEELMOVEMENT@{ub}
	By  default  BareED  starts  scrolling  when  the  wheel  of  a  mouse  is  turned  (rolled).  If you, for
	example,  have already a support program for wheel mice running, this behaviour of BareED would
	cause trouble. So you can disable it in order to allow only the support program to decide what to do.

		@{b}CONTEXTMENU@{ub}
	If you don't like or need the @{" context-menu " link context} of BareED you can disable it.

		@{b}ALWAYSPOPUP@{ub}
	The  normal  behaviour  of  BareED  is  to  allow every time when the right mouse button is pressed
	and  the  mouse pointer remains within the editor's drawing area to show the @{" context-menu " link context}. This
	can  be  annoying  when  using  a  patch  like  MagicMenu  -  especially when no block of text is
	marked.  Setting  this  tool-value  BareED  will  only show the @{" context-menu " link context} when the there is a
	marked block of text.

		@{b}VERYLASTCHANCESAVE@{ub}
	If  you  already specified the tool-type @{b}STDEXIT@{ub} then you may want to specify this tool-value, too.
	It  says nothing less as that the last prompt for saving will be suppressed - which can be annyoing
	when already confirmed the previously gotten request with "Abandon".

		@{b}PAGEMOVEMENT@{ub}
	Normally,  BareED  shifts  upon  moving  the  proportional gadget in the right area of the window as
	much  lines  as  fit into a page. Using this tool-values it shifts only single text lines - which is more
	compatible with other text editors. 

		@{b}SINGLESIGNDELETION@{ub}
	Used  only  for  Thai mode - it instructs BareED to delete complete Thai character sequences upon
	pressing the DELETE key on your keyboard.

		@{b}ENVACCESS@{ub}
	If  this  tool-value  (@{b}ENVAccess@{ub}) is not specified, every BareED instance will write upon activation
	to  the  ENV-archive  (@{b}ENV:@{ub})  its  ARexx port name - for easier access when dealing with Gui4CLI
	scripts. If you don't plan to use Gui4CLI scripts you can suppress BareED's ENV-access.
	NOTE:  If  the ENV-directory wasn't already set up by the system BareED cannot write anything to
	it but doesn't bother you with any kind of requester.

		@{b}KEEPBLOCKALIVE@{ub}
	Using  this  tool-value  will  lead  BareED  to  overwrite  highlighted  blocks of text upon entering a
	character  or  upon  inserting text clips. Normally, without using this tool-value, these blocks of text
	remain unchanged.


@{b}STATUSLINE@{ub}

	Enabling will force BareED to display at the bottom of the editor window a @{" Status Line " link statusline}.
	Please refer to the status line chapter for more information.


@{b}REDRAW=SMART@{ub}

	Normally,  without  this  tool-type,  BareED  will  open its editor window in "simple refresh" mode -
	what  means,  that  BareED itself is responsible to redraw the damaged (by other windows) regions.
	Due  to  the  idea behind BareED, this "restoring" is painfully slow. In order to speed up things, you
	can enter this tool-type and the systems takes now care about those damaged regions.

@{b}ZOOMBUTTON@{ub}							@{fg highlight}@{b}(OBSOLETE)@{ub}@{fg text}

	Although it was revised so that it should be more compatible - it shouldn't be used at all.
	The normal zoom gadget's behaviour was changed.

	--- OBSOLETE ----
	ZOOMBUTTON  will display an additional Zoom-Gadget which - in conjunction with the original -
	can be used to quickly change the editor window size without touching the Sizing-Gadget.


@{b}HORIZONTALSCALE=<scalefactor>@{ub}

	By  default,  BareED  opens  its  editor-window  full-sized.  You  may  limit the window-size by using a
	scale-factor.
	For  example,  if  "1/2"  was  chosen  it  instructed BareED to use only half of the normally used window
	width - in contrast to "3/7" - which is a little less tall than the half.

	Example:
		HORIZONTALSCALE=3/8

	NOTE: A project may come with different settings and thus these will be used!


@{b}VERTICALSCALE=<scalefactor>@{ub}

	The same as above, only for vertical size.


@{b}CENTERING=<CENTER|TOP|BOTTOM|LEFT|RIGHT>@{ub}

	You may specify also the appearance of BareED's window on the screen using this tool-type.
	@{b}CENTER@{ub} / @{b}CENTRE@{ub} will center the scaled window on the screen (both, horizontally and vertically).
	@{b}TOP@{ub} will place the window to the topmost position
	@{b}BOTTOM@{ub} will place the window at the bottommost position
	@{b}LEFT@{ub} - leftmost position
	@{b}RIGHT@{ub} - rightmost
	You may combine the attributes, for example:
		CENTERING=CENTRE|BOTTOM
	will place the window horizontally centered at the vertical, bottommost position.


@{b}RETURN=ENTER@{ub}

	... normally,  BareED's  default  behaviour  when  the  RETURN  key  is  pressed,  will result only in
	adding  a  linefeed  to  the  archive.  When  now this tool-type is active, BareED will automatically
	insert  after the linefeed has been added all those white spaces which led in the previous line, thus
	performing auto-indention - like pressing the ENTER key.


@{b}AUTOLOADDAC=<filename>@{ub}

	Using this tool-type BareED will allow you to start automatically your preferred DAC-application.
	NOTE:   Only   those   DAC-applications  who  will  normally  reside  in  the  DAC-menu  will  get
	supported. If you like to work with the C/C++ highlighter all you need to do is to enter its name:

	@{b}AUTOLOADDAC=THL C & C++ New@{ub}

	and it will be fired up by BareED upon start!


@{b}CURSORCLIPEND@{ub}

	...  by  default  BareED doesn't move the cursor to the end of the pasted text block but rather keeps
	the initial cursor position intact.
	If  you  want  the  more  common  behaviour where the cursor moves with the pasted text block you
	can set this tool-type.
	NOTE: In newer versions the page content is only shifted if necessary.


@{b}DRAWLINEFEEED@{ub}

	...  normally,  BareED  doesn't  display a LineFeed character. Using this tool-type it does display a
	synonym for that character ("¶"). Whatever this is good for...


@{b}FONT@{ub}

	...  using  this  tool-type  BareED doesn't inherit the system's default font but rather utilizes that one
	you specify.
	This tool-type may be of use to you in order using BareED as external text editor for other programs.


@{b}TIS620@{ub}
	... use this if you want permanent support for the Thai language.
	Please  note:  That  would require a font holding the TIS-620 glyphs and a keymap that assists you
	in order to enter them!
	See for more information: Enable @{" TIS-620 " link tis620} support in BareED.

@{b}THAIINPUTCHECK@{ub}
	The  level  of strictness how nitpicking BareED should be upon encountering invalid Thai character
	sequences.
	Possible values for this tool-type are:
		PASS THROUGH
		BASIC CHECK
		STRICT

@{b}FALLBACKPROJECT@{ub}						@{fg highlight}@{b}(NEW)@{ub}@{fg text}
	Utilize  the  tool-types  of  a  predefined  default  project  upon launching BareED when there is no
	existing icon for a document which urges BareED to utilize special aspects of this document.
	For further information see chapter @{" How do I customize BareED's launch " link usage}.

@endnode

@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

@node menus "BareED's special menu-items"


@{b}"IBM  compatible  Save"@{ub}

The  option  "IBM  compatible  Save"  allows  to  transmit  your archive from one computer platform to another
without  making  the  significant  changes  on your own. This means, however, too, that the complete layout of
your  archive  will  disappear  (on  your  Amiga)  but  it  becomes on an IBM computer very much resemble to
those  on  the  Amiga  created.  Those  changes  are  not  visible onscreen, however, when you invite the so
modified  file  again!  BareED  does  not do now anything other than to remove all line terminators (LineFeeds)
for  a  paragraph.  Because  it  is  in  fact  difficult  to  find  out  which  lines  appertain  to a paragraph on the
Amiga-platform,  you  must  prime first your archive. You eliminate all non-standard text features (for example
Escape  codes. As  next  you  select  then the right area boundary in the dialog box (if you use the Helvetica
font,  you  use a right edge of 153 signs). Then change your text so that a block format comes out in this case
(tabs  are  in  this case allowed). Backup now your archive onto a medium. BareED will combine now all lines
to an individual paragraph, that are not split into two parts and do not exceed your defaulted area boundary.


StAn  suggested  a  new menu item label since "IBM compatible save" may confuse users...
To  clarify  it's  job:  This  function exist to create an almost "MS-DOS" compatible file layout, maybe I should
change the name of the label to "MS-DOS save layout"...

@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}

@{b}"Catharsis Font?"@{ub}

In  order  to  use  this feature of BareED you have to install a special shared library, called @{fg highlight}"catharsis"@{fg text}, which
can be found within @{b}Aminet@{ub}.

@{fg highlight}Catharsis  library@{fg text} is a my attempt to make ugly fonts look a little bit nicer. For example the ordinary @{b}"times"@{ub} and
@{b}"helvetia"@{ub} fonts look quite well when rendered using @{fg highlight}Catharsis library@{fg text}.

@{fg highlight}Catharsis  library@{fg text}  renders  each  character  twice  into  the  display, where some pixel of the used font will be
displayed  in  a  different  colour.  Also,  some pixels of the used font will be displaced or even removed.
The  basic  font  on  disk  is  not  touched,  instead,  only  the font in memory is modified - but only visible for
applications, who deal with @{fg highlight}Catharsis library@{fg text}. BareED is one of them. :-)



*IBM		® International Business Machines

@endnode

@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

@node layout "Laying out a line or paragraph"


In  order  to  lay out the current line or paragraph you have to specify first the rightmost position -this position
is  taken  as  limit  for the text. To do this you can simply press "CTRL- B", which brings up a requester where
you can enter the rightmost position you allow.

BareED supports two block formats, one for normal texts and one for AmigaGuide compatible texts.

In order to lay out a normal text use "CTRL-A", but for AmigaGuide compatible texts use "CTRL-Z".

Characters in front of the current cursor position will be ignored in order to allow your individual arrangement.


@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}
+++ A REMARK +++
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ

If  you  lay  out  your  text  using  the  AmigaGuide compatible mechanism (CTRL-Z), ensure that a brace-left
character  is  introduced  through  the  at-sign  and  that  the  brace-left  character one following brace-right
character  has.  Otherwise,  in  case  not,  the  AmigaGuide  compatible  mechanism  is  broken  off and it will
become   enormously  difficult  to  restore  the  result  (text  layout)  to  that  of  your  original  layout.  Another
disadvantage is that italic strings may not be laid out correctly.


@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}
+++ A REMARK +++
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ

It  exists  a Rexx-script that can lay out your text using your leading characters (blanks, tabs, characters) and
it is called "Layout.rx". It's also reachable through the button-bank.
It's  limit  is designed for 640 pixel wide screens but you can change this if you edit this script and replace the
line:

rightmost = 640

with your desired value (e.g. 1024).

@endnode

@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

@node linewrap "BareED's Pseudo Line Wrapper"

BareED's "Line Wrap" feature.

As  you already know, BareED does not limit any line of text to a maximum of characters.
In  order to avoid scrolling horizontally to have all characters visible a pseudo "Line Wrap" mechanism had to
be introduced in order to let BareED deal with a fixed number of characters per line.
Turning  "Line  Wrap"  on,  means  that  BareED  from  now  on  tries  to  make use of this (faked) mechanism.
Whether it is clever or suits your needs you have to find out on your own. For me it fits.

BareED  does  not  offer you the ability to specify a width limit, where any word behind this mark is mapped to
a new line, instead, BareED wraps the text ever in front of the right window border.
Turning  on now "IBM compatible save" has a different meaning when "Line Wrap" is turned on. BareED treats
then  the  text  lying  in  the  editor  as  a plain one and thus creates a plain and compatible one - which for
example,  can  be  loaded  via  Microsoft's  Editor  (combining  splitted  lines and terminate them with carriage
return codes).

It's  indeed  useful  if  you write on your Amiga text fragments and copy these to your Windows environment in
order to create out of it (let's say) a HTML file.

Without  "IBM  compatible  save"  turned  on,  other  text  editors  (even  on the Amiga) may not recognize the
layout  of  the  saved  text  -  since  lines, which do belong together, are split up by BareED only through the
combination of a blank- and linefeed character at line's end.
Saving  such  a  file without "Line Wrap" turned on, will result in a text file with many space + linefeeds at end
of those lines, which in turn may stop other text editors than BareED to handle the loaded file properly.

There  is  an  automatic  character-mapper  built  into  BareED  -  in  case a file is loaded in and this file was
encoded for Microsoft operating systems - which use a slightly different characater map.

Please  do  not  use  the  "Line  Wrap"  feature  in case you're editing a large text file because BareED would
become  painfully  slow  since  it  has  to  re-layout  the  entire  archive via copying of characters in order to
achieve "Line Wrap".

@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}

Thanks  to  annotations  made  by  Joseph  regarding  the  Line  Wrap  mode, the entire Line Wrap mode was
revised in order to allow the displaying of the real line number - and not anymore some kind of "pizza".

@endnode

@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

@node buttons "BareED's button interface"

Before  you  start  to  use this feature of BareED, you have to make sure that you own a 68040 or better CPU,
the  operating  system  of  version  3.0  or  better  and  at  least  130  Kbytes of free memory (for the graphical
details).  Ensure also that you are using a 256-colour screen with a resolution of at least 800 x 600 pixels (do
not  use the button interface if you only have one of the native Amiga graphic devices!). If this does not scare
you, then just read ahead.

BareED  offers  a  button  interface  that  is  disabled  by default, due to the memory consumption and the time
needed to set up this button interface. If you own a 68040+ CPU, however, you may wish to use it.

No  image  for  the  button  bank  of  BareED  is limited to something. This means that the imagery may differ in
width, height, depth and colour.

By  default  no  pens  of  the  knobs  are  reserved  in order to give any picture viewer the ability to view any
imagery  in  the  closest  colour match. This can lead BareED to view those knobs in false colours when there
are  no  more pens free, or when a picture viewer overrides BareED used pens - but this can be changed by
BareED  at  any  time,  unfortunately, you have to explicitly tell BareED if the button bank appears ugly. If you
don't agree with this, use the tool type setting that forces BareED to reserve these pens.

You  should,  although  there  is  no  such  hard  coded  limit,  limit your image to a height that can fit into the
window when there is also enough room to display one, single text line.

The  imagery  themselves  have  to  be  created through the use of an available paint program, e. g. Personal
Paint.  Your  render  image  and  the select image have to be of same size. You must define the border for the
knob on your own - if you want a border to separate the buttons.

When  you  have  made  your  imagery,  backup  the  render  and the select image for each knob to disk as a
single  file, where the render image is placed at the top and the select image at the bottom of this new created
picture - and no row splits them up!

	 ____________
	|	       |
	|	       |
	|	       |	< Render Image
	|	       |
	|____________|	\\___________ no room between
	|ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ|	/
	|	       |
	|	       |	< Select Image
	|	       |
	|	       |
	 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ


@{b}DETAILED DESCRIPTION:
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}


BareED's  button  interface  is  nothing  else  than  a  groin  with graphic symbols. While clicking one of these
symbols, BareED carries out an action, e.g. opening a file requester.

BareED offers a button interface that can be changed by the user to form his individual wishes.

Therefore  BareED  allows  you  to  change  the  imagery  for  the  button interface knobs and the order of the
knobs.  In order to achieve this you must edit the text file "Button.cfg", e.g. with BareED itself, - which must be
placed in the root directory of the executable file BareED!

If  you turn on the menu item "Use Knob-Bank?", BareED will read in the file "Button.cfg" and examine this file
according to codewords.

Therefore,  indices  are very important since no file names are defaulted but these used indices point at intern
functions of BareED.

Indices,  which  are  supported by BareED, are settled in the field of 1 to 63; BareED sets up functions at your
disposal, which DOS commands can fire up beginning with index 40.

The  indices,  beginning  with  index 40, ARexx macros can also be assigned by means of the DOS command
"RX", so that through a simple mouse click on one of these buttons a macro direct can be started.

A  command line that is understood by BareED must be introduced by the index (the index is a usual number),
followed from a comma that itself the path and file name of the graphic symbol of this function connect.

A valid coding line would then look like this:

	@{b}3,SYS:Images/Save.btn@{ub}
	ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ

where  number  3  represents  the  index,  and  "@{b}SYS:@{ub}"  indicates  the  partition of the hard disk. The directory
"@{b}Images@{ub}"  as a consequence, contains for our example another file by the name of "@{b}Save.btn@{ub}" that the graphic
symbol which a function was assigned contains.
For  the  case,  that  you  do not like the symbols enclosed by me, you proceed as follows in order to replace
the symbols made out by me through your own symbols:

The first step that you must do is to start a paint program of your choice in order to paint two small pictures.

The  colour  palette  chosen  by  you  is  only  being  of secondary importance, however, you should choose
these pictures less than 48 screen points in level and upright direction.
It goes without saying that the two pictures with it should have the same scales.
Put the two pictures directly on top of each other so that no space occurs between the two pictures.
Now take the two pictures as one pencil and store it in the IFF format with at the most 256 colours.

Now copy the enclosed tool "BitMapSaver" into the C-directory of your System, e.g.

	@{b}Copy ...../BitMapSaver to C:@{ub}
	ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ

You invoke the tool BitMapSaver as follows:

@{b}1> c:bitmapsaver NAME_OF_IMAGE to NAME_OF_KNOB opt raw rawhdr pen cmap rgb32@{ub}

If the path- or filename of the image file contains spaces, enclose them in double quotes.

The tool BitMapSaver will create an image that can directly be read by the program BareED.

The  next  step  you  have to do is to edit the text file "Button.cfg" which describes this function and the image
you want to change.

We assume as an example that you would like to change the button which describes the backup function.

The  index  which  indicates  the  backup function was determined by me as function 3. We now search in the
file  "Button.cfg"  for  the  line  which begins with number 3. According to number 3, followed by a comma, the
path and file name of the image file used currently stands.
Change  the  path  and  file  name so that this now points at your newly defined image file. If you now start the
program BareED and turn on the button groin, your image file appears instead of the made out by me.

As  mentioned  above  already,  allows  BareED  it  you  to carry out a DOS command, by which the required
coding line is hardly treated more heavily than a normal one that points at an intern function of BareED.

In  memory;  a valid coding line consists of the index which points to a function and the file name of the image
file!

@{b}nn,path&filename@{ub}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ
New  is  now,  that  according  to the file name of the symbol (image file) separated by a space character and
included in parentheses, a valid AmigaDOS coding line follows.

@{b}nn,path&filename @{fg highlight}(AmigaDOS_command_line)@{fg text}@{ub}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ
In  case  you  want  to  have an ARexx macro file executed by means of the DOS command "RX", the correct
coding line reads like this:

@{b}40,path&filename_of_image_file @{fg highlight}(SYS:RexxC/RX your_rexx_macro.rx)@{fg text}@{ub}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ
Please  do  not  forget  that  only  the  indices  which  are  settled  from  index 40 up to index 63, will allow it,
AmigaDOS coding lines to carry out.

By  the  way,  if  you  would  like  to start a ARexx macro file by means of the "@{b}RX@{ub}" command, you indicate as
command  file  "@{b}SYS:RexxC/RX@{ub}"  where  the  word  "@{b}RX@{ub}"  should  be  capitalized because BareED then starts
automatically the Rexx server - if the eleventh and the twelfth character to the word "@{b}RX@{ub}" show!

@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}


CHANGE ORDER:
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ

To  vary  the order of the buttons, it satisfies, the line that the index of the corresponding symbol represents to
displace in the file "Button.cfg".

Example:
The symbol which saving represents should be strobed before the symbol which loading represents.

The  only  you  have  to  do,  is  the  line that begin with number 3 (save) to present that line, that begins with
number 2 (load).

2,knobs/Load.btn
3,knobs/Save.btn

	changed to

3,knobs/Save.btn
2,knobs/Load.btn

Easy, isn't it?

@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}


REMARKS:
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ

In  order  to  insert  remarks  into  the  file "Button.cfg" it satisfies remarks to turn a semicolon on. BareED will
ignore  everything  behind  a semicolon up to end of line. Semicolons are also suitable to eliminate statements
instead of to remove completely this!

Examples:
2,knobs/Load.btn	; the load image
; 3,knobs/Save.btn	removed save image off button bank

@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}


INDICES:
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ

Following indices are assigned to these functions:

*	0	exit BareED
*	1	move gadget within BareED's right window border
	2	load a new file
	3	save existing file out of editor
	4	create a new, blank editor surround, ready to enter characters
*	5	close the current editor surrounding
	6	print document
	7	select screen mode and use it
	8	select tab-step and use it
	9	select a new font and use it
	10	select pencils for document
*	11	change palette of screen
 	12	snapshot marked block and save it as clip to the clipboard
	13	insert clip in clipboard into current document
	14	undo one, remembered action
	15	write marked block to disk
	16	insert a file into the current document
	17	open the find-requester
	18	open the replace-requester
	19	open the go-to-requester
	20	arrange current paragraph to block layout
	21	arrange current paragraph to block layout but in an AmigaGuide compatible manner
*	22	open requester to execute an ARexx-macro
*	23	set global preferences

(* = Unsupported)

@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}


BACKGROUND PATTERN:
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ

BareED  let  you  also  choose  the  background  pattern  and colour beside the imagery and the vertical and
horizontal distance between each image and the border of the knob-bank. There are synonyms to choose it.

FILPAT		synonym for fill-pattern
PATPEN	synonym for pattern-pen
VSPACE	synonym for vertical spacing
HSPACE	synonym for horizontal spacing
ONEPAL	synonym for one palette


In  order  to  make  them  available  to  BareED these synonyms have to be entered in the same file where the
knobs have been described, Button.cfg .

An example could look like this:

FILPAT=0
PATPEN=0
VSPACE=0
HSPACE=0
ONEPAL=0

The  FILPAT  is  a  long  word  representing  a  mask for set and unset pixels. It can be entered as a decimal,
hexadecimal or dual number.

FILPAT=1431677610	; hexadecimal ($) 5555AAAA, dual (%) 01010101.01010101.10101010.10101010
PATPEN=2		; use a white pattern (on my system)
VSPACE=1		; use between each image (and between the pattern border and the image itself)
			; one vertical line
HSPACE=1		; ditto for horizontal
ONEPAL=1		; all imagery will have the same palette thus tell BareED to compute the palette
			; only once (30% faster)

@endnode

@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

@node statusline "BareED's Status Line"

@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}

The StatusLine

@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}

In order to enable this feature you have to enter in BareED's icon this tool-type:

@{b}STATUSLINE@{ub}

You also have to specify which kinds of arguments should be displayed.
Each argument is introduced by the percent-sign ("%") and divided by the comma (",") or bar-sign ("|").

Supported arguments are:

	%n		Name of archive
	%s		Size in bytes of archive
	%a		Alterations made to the archive
	%m (ą)		Mode currently utilized
	%o		Overall lines in archive
	%l		Line where the cursor stays in
	%c		Column where the cursor stays at
	%v		Vertical blank interrupt counter - used for DAC and display synchronisation
	%h		Refresh rate in Hertz of the utilized monitor
	%b		Buffer size in Kbytes
	%k		Key-code of the character under the cursor
	%u		Clipboard unit number currently utilized (use "CTRL 0 to 9" to change it)

Hence, the status line could be entered as:

STATUSLINE=%n,%s,%c,%l
	or
STATUSLINE=%n|%s|%c|%l

You may specify one additional text for each argument:

STATUSLINE=Name%n|Size%s|Column%c|Line%l

	or

STATUSLINE=Name: %n|Size: %s|Column: %c|Line: %l

Blanks (spaces) placed between the additional text and the argument itself are not skipped!
Though  blanks  at the end of an argument will! So, even the following example looks quite different compared
to the above, it's nevertheless identical:

STATUSLINE=Name: %n  |Size: %s  |Column: %c  |Line: %l

Leading blanks for arguments will be skipped as well:

STATUSLINE=  Name: %n  |  Size: %s  |  Column: %c  |  Line: %l

@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}

The  status  line  tries  always  to  display  the  argument  first and then the additional text. If the additional text
doesn't  fit  into  the  bounding box, it will be left out. If the argument itself does not fit completely, its rendering
colour (normally black) will change - as indicator that you cannot rely on what you see.


@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}


@{b}*ą)@{ub}  The  mode  indicates whether to "insert" @{b}i@{ub} or "overwrite" @{b}o@{ub} characters, whether "infinitive" @{b}~@{ub} or "word wrap"
@{b}w@{ub}  (line  wrap)  is  used  and  whether  the  archive  is  protected  against  modifications @{b}p@{ub} - the minus sign @{b}-@{ub}
indicates unprotected and last but not least if the capslock key is locked @{b}U@{ub} or not @{b}u@{ub} .

@endnode

@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

@node rexx "The Amiga Rexx Interface of BareED"


First of all, this chapter and in general the ARexx-interface of BareED are under construction!


ARexx  scripts can indirectly drive BareED, but at the moment BareED does not offer to execute ARexx scripts
with one exception: the button interface of BareED gives you direct access to such scripts.
BareED  is  able  to  deal  with  strings  containing  up  to  three  macro-commands  where  the  first is called
"Command-Index", the second "Object-Index" and the third "Parameter-Index".

So instead of writing:

GetAmountChars
 You write
Get Amount Chars

Which  is  first  better  to  read and second for me easier to parse. The disadvantage is that it may collide with
reserved  ARexx  symbol  names  or  functions,  e.g.  Set  Error  Off,  where  ·"ERROR"·  is a reserved ARexx
command.

One goal of BareED's ARexx interface is the non-case-sensitive handling of passed strings. So you can write:

	get amount chars

		Or

	'get amount chars'			«« enclosed in single quotes
	'get aMOunt chARs'
	'GET AMOUNT CHARS'

It's  non  important  to  BareED! BareED splits a command line (string) into the above stated index' where hash
values are used instead of simple string comparison.

Currently  BareED  has  got  an  ARexx  interface with more than 80 macro-commands but only a few call the
appropriate routines (under construction). Supported are:

				additional string
				ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ|
						  |
Command-Index	Object-Index	Parameter-Index	«astr»	RESULT
@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}
SET
		ERROR		ON  |  OFF		-none-	( useful when debugging )
		ECHO		ON  |  OFF		-none-	( useful when debugging )
		FONT		"times.font,13"		-none-	should be clear....
		FONTSTYLE	0,1,2,3 or combined		-none-		try!
		CLIPUNIT		0 - (almost) ~		-none-	0 suggested for textfiles
		FIND		STRING		"string"	-none-	the string to look for
		REPLACE	STRING		"string"	-none-	find string replaced with this one

		FINDMODE	-none-			-none-	Set default mode, case sensitive but no word only search
				NORMAL			-none-	non case sensitive search
				WORDONLY		-none-	word only search

		MARGIN		RIGHT	"number" 		-none-	set right margin in number of letters
		TAB		SIZE	"number" 		-none-	"number" in amount of characters
		BLOCKSTART	-none-			-none-	set start point for marked area or erase it
		BLOCKEND	-none-			-none-	set end point for marked area or erase it (not necessary, anyhow...)
		MODE
				INSERT			-none-	Set editor mode to "INSERT" characters
				OVERWRITE		-none-	Set editor mode to "OVERWRITE" characters
		WORDWRAP	ON  |  OFF		-none-	Set editor mode to "Linewrap" or disable it
@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}
GET
		ARCHIVESTART	 -none-			address memory where characters start
		ARCHIVEEND	-none-			address memory where characters end
		REGION		-none-			address allocated memory for storage
		REGION		SIZE			amount allocated memory for storage in bytes
		ARCHIVENAME	-none-			filename without path
		FILENAME	-none-			filename inclusive path

		AMOUNT
				CHARS			amount characters in archive
				LINES			amount lines in archive
				CHANGES		amount of modifications
		CURRENT
				CHAR			RC    single character (RC unequal zero if end of archive)
				LINE			RC    complete string line (RC unequal zero if end of archive
							         or only a paragraph)
				COLUMN			offset in number of spaces in current line
		CURSOR
				X			offset (in number of characters) in current line
				Y			current line

		BVERSION	-none-			packed: version (high word), revision (low word)
		FONT		-none-			string: fontname - terminated by a comma - then font height
		TAB		SIZE			amount of space characters a tab takes up
		CHARWIDTH	"char"			characters width in number of pixels
		BLOCK		-none-			add contents of clip to archive
		MODE		-none-			Get string either "INSERT" or "OVERWRITE" -> editor's edit mode
				INSERT			0 if "OVERWRITE" is used, otherwise 1
				OVERWRITE		0 if "INSERT" is used, otherwise 0
				WORDWRAP		0 if it WORDWRAP isn't turned on otherwise 1 (turned on)
		PROGDIR		-none-			Returns as string BareED's home-directory
