@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

@node rxfaults "Amiga Rexx problems"

__
 I	Unknown command
ŻŻŻŻ

When  you  encounter  a  problem  that you cannot track down it's very likely that a function either of the rexx
master  or  a  rexx  support  library  returned  an error or even no error in the RC variable. In case that occurs
ARexx tells you that the command (here BareED) returned the value 10.

For example I used this and similar fragments which caused a lot of error messages until it was solved:

Address BareED.1
Options Results

Delay( 2)
Put Char '0A'X

Seems  to  be okay to me. I opened the "rexxsupport.library" and therewith the Delay() function could be used.
The  mistake  that  I  made  was that I didn't cared about the RC variable where a function passes the result of
the function.

In  the  ARexx  manual  is  stated  that  a  returned  function code may not be explicit called, it's automatically
done.  I know that but never thought that the result of Delay() is passed immediately to BareED. In the example
code above the ARexx-Server made following of the code:

Address BareED.1
Options Results

Delay( 2)
0				<<<< !!!!
Put Char '0A'X

When  BareED  encountered  the  character  zero  ("0")  it  didn't  know how to handle it so it returned 10 (not
known  by  me)!  This  mistake is not only visible when "Options Results" is used (application function, do and
return a result).


This  problem  to solve is very easy; call a function so that ARexx knows that you don't care about a result. In
the code fragment above it is done through:

Address BareED.1
Options Results

Call Delay( 2)			<<<< !!!!
Put Char '0A'X

The  "CALL" command indicates that the RC variable has got no influence on the further "programme course".
Thus  RC  is  taken  as  unset by ARexx and therewith ignored, which leads ARexx to continue with "Put Char
'0A'X"  instead  of  "0".  Nevertheless, the return code of the function Delay() can be check; it's not placed in
the RC variable but in the RESULT variable!


@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}

___
 I I	BareED's macros become not recognize
ŻŻŻŻŻŻ

As  already  stated  somewhere  in  this  document,  BareED  has got a non case-sensitive interface to Arexx
where  a  letter is ever treated like it would have been entered in upper case. The next is that BareED doesn't
use   single   macro   commands,   e.g.   "MoveCursorArchiveend",   instead   it  will  support  "Move  Cursor
Archiveend".  This  has  got  the  advantage  to  be  more  readable  but can put anybody in trouble if he/she
doesn't know which symbols ARexx and BareED reserve!

So a simple line like:

Set Error Off

Will  cause  trouble  because  "ERROR" is a reserved ARexx and BareED macro name! To avoid this enclose
any probably from both used macro name in single quotes, e.g.:

'Set Error Off'

Now  this  string  is passed through to BareED instead of being analysed by ARexx, because ARexx treats the
three words as one single line and therewith as a macro (which it does not understand).

Also, variable names can cause trouble, e.g.:

Get Amount Lines
Lines = RESULT		< OK

....bla bla bla

Get Amount Lines		< ERROR
Lines = RESULT

In  the  example  I  misused  a reserved macro name as variable name, "Lines". Until the second "Get Amount
Lines"  is  encountered  all  goes  as  it  should, when now ARexx analyses the second "Get Amount Lines" it
encounters  the  "Amount"  macro  name  followed  by  the  "Lines" variable. If "Lines" has got the value 1300
ARexx would pass this string to BareED:

Get Amount 1300

Of  course  BareED  cannot  handle  this.  To  avoid  this there are several solutions, first: do not use variable
names,  which  will  also  be  used as macro commands by BareED, second: enclose the macro name, which
collides with the variable name in single quotes, e.g.:

> Get Amount 'Lines' <, or which is in my opinion better, enclose all macro names in single quotes:

'Get Amount Lines'

As  already  told,  it  doesn't  bother  BareED if you write in lower or upper case or in mixed form. So you can
even write:

'gEt aMoUnT lineS'

BareED knows how to handle this.


@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}

____
 I I I	Not know problems by author
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ

Room for your extraordinary experiences with BareED and ARexx...


@endnode

@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

@node dac "DAC port - or what does it mean at all"

The DAC interface of BareED.

What is DAC mean to be?

DAC  stands  for  @{b}@{fg highlight}D@{ub}@{fg text}irect  @{b}@{fg highlight}A@{ub}@{fg text}pplication  @{b}@{fg highlight}C@{ub}@{fg text}ommunication  and  is used by BareED to offer solutions for a problem
which isn't supported by BareED natively, for example @{fg shine}text highlighting@{fg text}.

DAC  also  means  that  the interface doesn't make use of system routines there where it is possible as well as
of advantage.

Contrary  to  other interfaces this one requires no concessions to the application used by BareED which shall
be executed to overcome a problem.
It's  of  no  importance  whether  the  application  was  translated using a high level language or an assembler
since  BareED  carries  out  all required things in secrecy which are needed to execute this application and it
therefore should be very easy to write an application for BareED .

The most common expression for such an application comes from the English and is called: "Plug-in".

Oh yes; since BareED is different compared to other text editors this thing is called here: "DAC application" ...

TECHNICAL NOTE:
Normally,  a  plug-in  is  a  shared library or some kind of routine which is executed by the main process (the
text editor for example).
Here,  speaking  of  BareED,  a plug-in is a normal AmigaDOS process - which can use functions of BareED
and not vice versa!
The  aim  behind  this  idea  is  to  let  the  main  process (text editor) stay alive although a plug-in may have
crashed.

@{b}@{fg highlight}The  DAC  port  got  a  major  overhaul  because  on  slow  machines the asynchronous message mechanism
wasn't - hmmm - optimal...
Now,  it  supports  a  synchronous  message  system with double buffered messages and also the back-up of
currently not attachable messages.
Even on a 68020 it should now give best results without colour faults.@{ub}@{fg text}


I describe this interface now.
@{fg shine}_______________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}


DAC applications usually belong into this drawer:

@{b}BareED/DAC/@{ub}

This  has  moreover  the  advantage that BareED includes these files in the DAC menu automatically and you
can comfortably select these with the mouse.

If no file is in the DAC drawer, BareED won't represent any DAC menu with entries either.

At  present  up  to  16  such DAC menu items will be represented and therefore also 16 DAC applications can
be  selected  and  started  with  the  mouse.  After  one  of  the  selected  DAC-application  was launched by
BareED, normally selecting its item once more in the DAC menu will bring up the DAC application's GUI.

If  the  DAC  menu  has  exhausted  its  capacity of 16 entries, all following DAC applications aren't listed any
more.  Though,  you  still  can  start  these  manually,  by  means  of  the  key  combination  "CTRL-D" which
represents  a  file-requester  where you can comfortably select and start the concerned DAC application with
the mouse.

@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}

@{b}The THL applications@{ub} (Text Highlighting applications):
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ

The  correct  term  is  syntax  highlighting,  no  question,  however,  I do not want to use this highbrow term in
connection  with  BareED's ability to show texts in different colours, since a certain measure of analysis is the
basis  for  genuine  syntax  highlighting,  which  the  THL  applications  don't  carry out. They simply compare
strings...

In result of that, I call it simply text highlighting, which, in my opinion, suit better the THL applications.


@{b}Text highlighting versus syntax highlighting.@{ub}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ

What's the difference between text and syntax highlighting?

Text  highlighting  will  only  highlight  those  strings  which  do  have  an accordance with strings somewhere
saved  in  the  concerned  plug-in.  In  principle  it's just a simple string comparision; if the encountered string
corresponds to a certain, the encountered string is highlighted.

Syntax  highlighting  in  contrast  needs  to evaluate clauses, terms, and in addition, has to examine the entire
line  of  text  before  a  string  or  word can be highlighted - in dependence on the validity of the encountered
string.  Syntax  highlighting  needs  therefore  much  more  CPU  resources which is unsuitable for text editors
which gather the required information in real time, such as text editors like BareED.

Let's look at this example (ARexx):


@{fg highlight}CALL CLOSE 'file_port'@{fg text}


It's  a  valid  code  snippet  for  the ARexx interpreter. Here the file handle called @{fg shine}"file_port"@{fg text} will be closed and
the @{fg shine}CALL@{fg text} command indicates that there is no return code of interest.

Without  real  syntax  highlighting  a  text editor cannot display it correctly, since @{fg shine}CLOSE@{fg text} can be also used as
some kind of variable:


@{fg highlight}close = "This is the closing string"@{fg text}


So,  in  the  example  above, only the @{fg shine}CALL@{fg text} command and the string @{fg shine}"file_port"@{fg text} will be highlighted upon using
text  highlighting,  whilst upon using real syntax highlighting also the @{fg shine}CLOSE@{fg text} term will be highlighted, because
the entire line of text is evaluated before any outputs will be made.

BareED's  ARexx  plug-in  (DAC  application)  is using text highlighting for speed reasons, which then cannot
handle  cases  as  the one stated above, unless it would use some kind of work-around. Fortunately, @{fg shine}CLOSE@{fg text}
is  a  function  and  normally  a  function  should  be used only in conjunction with parentheses, so the above
example should be changed to:


@{fg highlight}CALL CLOSE('file_port')@{fg text}


then,  even  the  DAC-THL  ARexx  application can handle such lines of text correctly, because it contains a
work-around  which  checks whether a function name (here @{fg shine}CLOSE@{fg text}) has got a opening parenthesis attached.
Unfortunately,  this  check  for  parentheses  would  lead  to  fail  to highlight @{fg shine}IF@{fg text} or @{fg shine}WHILE@{fg text} keywords, in cases
where parentheses would be used, e.g.:


@{fg highlight}IF (a < b)@{fg text}


because @{fg shine}IF@{fg text} is not a function name, but a command.
In  order  to  avoid  such fails, an additional check for the @{fg shine}IF@{fg text} and @{fg shine}WHILE@{fg text} keywords is implemented. But IF and
WHILE are the only keywords where this check is applied.

ARexx  has  got  the  disadvantage  for text highlighting applications that one term or keyword can be used for
multiple cases:


@{fg highlight}Numeric Fuzz 5@{fg shine}    /* Fuzz used as argument to Numeric */@{fg text}
@{fg highlight}fuzz = FUZZ()@{fg shine}      /* fuzz is a variable and FUZZ a function */@{fg text}
@{fg highlight}Say fuzz@{fg shine}              /* fuzz is a variable */@{fg text}

Because ARexx treats strings case insensitive there is no difference in these forms: @{fg shine}fuzz, Fuzz, FUZZ@{fg text}!
And without parsing the entire line of text it is not possible to handle all cases correctly.


@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}

Since  BareED  has  got  a built-in a colour choosing aid, DAC applications can make use of this, though it's
up to the application, at which executed action the colour choosing aid is represented.
This  colour  choosing  aid  is  "baptized"  by me "ColorChooser" (although no original name, it is meaningful,
however).

If  you  have  started  a DAC application by means of the corresponding menu entry and you select this entry
again  a  graphic  user interface should appear, within you should be able to call the colour choosing aid. It's
completely  left  to  the  discretion  of  the  DAC  application,  whether  this  characteristic  (ColorChooser)  is
represented  or  not,  and  also  that  "how". Have a look at the concerned application's documentation "how"
and "when" it will call the colour choosing aid.

@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}

You should always keep in the back of your mind that DAC applications are independent, dependent programs.

Gee?

Dependent according to:
	DAC applications always need BareED to carry out any actions.

Independent according to:
	DAC  applications  are  ordinary  programs  according  to the Amiga operating system, what means
	that  they  use  an  independent (from BareED's view) memory location and in turn - not being able
	to  take  BareED,  in  case  of a crash, into nirvana with them (under rarely circumstances they do,
	however).

@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}

In  case  you  want  to  write  a  plug-in for BareED please read the developer material - which has been not
enclosed to the user archive (BareED.lha), instead you need the file BareED_Dev.lha.


@endnode

@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

@node strange "Strange behaviour of BareED - with a good reason!"

@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}

BareED is different - and so sometimes BareED's behaviour will look like a bug but rather is a feature.

Normally,  when  you  quit  a  text  editor this text editor shows up a message in case the file you have edited
was changed but not saved.
Then  you  can  choose what you want to do - save it or ignore the request. After the file was backed up - or
not - depends on your response, this editor's window is closed.

BareED goes now a completely different way.
It  first closes the screen (in case one has been opened) and the editor's window! Then a message is shown if
the text was changed but not saved!
But why?
In  case  you  are  already  low  on RAM - and the screen and window remain open, it could happen that the
ASL file-requester cannot be shown - due to lack of RAM!
But  BareED  frees some resources first (screen and window) in order to give the system back some RAM and
thus the chance to display the file-requester is greater.

So, it's a feature and not a bug!

If  you  don't  like  this  behaviour  of  BareED  you  can  enable  the  standard  exit by enabling the tool-type
STDEXIT in BareED's icon.

The slider gadget shown within the right window border does not base on lines, but rather on "pages".
Clicking  with  the  mouse  in  front or beyond the knob moves the cursor to the revious / next page instead of
the line.
This  is  required  by  me  because  I need BareED to deal with large files and therefore I need a possibility to
chop quickly around pages.


@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}

@endnode

@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

@node catharsis "Catharsis - or BareED's attempt to make the times font look nicer..."

@{b}"Using Catharsis Font"@{ub}

In  order  to  use  this feature of BareED you have to install a special shared library, called @{fg highlight}"catharsis"@{fg text}, which
can be found within @{b}Aminet@{ub}.

@{fg highlight}Catharsis library@{fg text} must be copied to your LIBS: drawer in order for BareED to access it.

The  @{fg highlight}Catharsis  library@{fg text}  is  used  in order to render texts to the display. Normally, any so called bitmap-related
font is rendered using one colour, the foreground colour.

When  now  BareED  uses  the  @{fg highlight}Catharsis  library@{fg text}  in  order  to  print  out texts, an additional colour is used to
display  this  text.  This slows down the rendering process by factor 2, but makes out of ugly looking texts well
looking ones.
This  is done by generating out of the original @{b}"font's bitmap"@{ub} another one where some pixels will be displaced
or added.
The  basic  font  on  disk  is  not  modified!
Then, this @{b}"font bitmap"@{ub} is attached to a font-structure, ready to use by the OS functions to draw texts.

Now  the  basic  @{b}"bitmap  font"@{ub}  is  rendered  using  the text colour to the display and then using the additional
@{b}"bitmap font"@{ub} in a different colour, basing on your chosen colour values for background and foreground.

@endnode

@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

@node colorchooser "The ColorChooser - a standardized interface to change colours"

@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}

The colour choosing aid (ColorChooser)

@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}

The  colour  choosing  aid  consist  of  some elements by whose interplay special keywords, character strings
and  comparable  things  can  be  changed  in  their  colour and luminance. BareED takes advantage of some
external,  disk  resident  routines,  so-called  classes,  which  make  it  possible  for  you to change coloured
pens in a simple way, which could for example be taken advantage of by DAC applications.

There  are  these  routines  only  as  of the operating system version 3.0, it isn't possibly to use these features
under version 2 of the operating system.

Also,  these  coloured  pens  mentioned  above  are available in a special version only as of version 3 of the
operating system.


The  ColorChooser  of BareED make excessive use of these special coloured pens, namely "shared pens", in
which   a   minimum   of  32  pens  should  be  available;  BareED  otherwise  won't  be  able  to  display  the
ColorChooser, and you are therefore robbed of your possibility amending colours.

If  you  have difficulties in displaying the ColorChooser, you could go back to a screen for a short time, which
provides  more  than  32  colours  -- by means of the possibility that BareED offers to display an own, colour
intensive  screen. If you then have changed the colours to your taste, you can close this screen and go back
again to the screen which you use normally and which is preferred by you - in order to work there further.

@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}

Anyhow, it should be really self-explaining.
You  pick  a  text  shown  in  the  ListView  and  the  ColorWheel  and  GradientSlider  gadgets  are changed
accordingly,  or  you  change  a  colour  via  the  ColorWheel  gadget  and  the  ListView and GradientSlider
gadgets are updated accordingly.
Same happens when you adjust the colour via the GradientSlider gadget.

@endnode


@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

@node wheel "Mouse wheel support"

@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}

The mouse  wheel is used to scroll 25 percent of page contents (but at least one line).

Pressing  the mouse wheel button will display an image. Now, any mouse movement (vertical) is used to scroll
up  or down; the farer you move the mouse pointer away from its initial position, the faster you scroll (speed: 1
to 15 lines per second).

When  the  mouse movement image is displayed and you turn the wheel of your mouse while smooth scrolling
is used, the smooth scrolling is disabled for the time consumed to perform this operation.

NOTE:	If  you  enabled  the  tool-type  "SMOOTHSCROLL"  it's very likely that BareED isn't able to scroll
	with  the fastest speed possible, because rendering an image into the display and also scrolling the
	entire page several times means a huge speed lost!
	Displaying the image means also to fiddle around with a bottle-neck!
	I  made  a  lot  of  tests  in  order to find out where the most time is "wasted" - and it turned out that
	displaying the image takes more time than scrolling the entire page several times...

@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}

In order to avoid "stumbling" texts, you may specify @{" SCROLLTIMEOUT=AUTO " link settings} - and see if it fits for you.

@endnode


@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

@node tis620 "Limited Thai language support"

@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}

Foreword:

Without  the great enthusiasm and efforts made by Dr. Lyndon Hill the Thai language support of BareED would
not ever have been possible, so, many, many thanks!

As  you  already  may  have  guessed,  I,  as  a  mid-European don't speak Thai at all. For me Thai is a very
abstract  language  because  a  character  is  not  represented by only a single character but through several
symbols  (my  point  of  view...)!  If Dr. Hill had not already made Amiga-bitmap fonts using the TIS-620 matrix
base, no Thai language support would have been possible.

A lot of time was invested by both of us to let an Amiga text editor natively support the Thai language!

@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}

If  you  want BareED permanently supporting the TIS-620 character layout and the special edit mode that has
to take place, you may add this tooltype to BareED's icon: 

@{b}TIS620 @{ub}
 
If you only want for a session to turn TIS-620 support on, enable in the edit menu the item
@{b}"Thai mode?"@{ub}. 

In order to display Thai glyphs you need a font that contains these characters. 

You may download them from Dr. Hills homepage "@{b}http://www.lyndonhill.com/Projects/thaionamiga.html@{ub}" and
install them.

In addition, you should also download and install the needed keymap provided by Dr. Hill.

If these basic steps were made by you, you are now able to enter and edit Thai letters in BareED!

@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}

@{b}@{fg highlight}The following is more of technical nature so my excuses first!@{fg text}@{ub}

Upon switching into TIS-620 mode, BareED's edit behaviour will change:

BareED will from now on investigate each entered or displayed character for its spacing ability.

There  are  now  spacing  characters  and  non-spacing-markers  as  found  in  Unicode,  but  in  contrast to
ASCII/LATIN-1 which consists only of spacing characters.

If  you  enter  an  invalid  character (a non-spacing-marker at the start of a line - for example) the cursor will
not move away from its initial position and no new character will be displayed.

If  you  enter  a  spacing  character  and  afterwards  a non-spacing-marker this non-spacing-marker will be
pasted  to  the  spacing character without moving the cursor one position further to the right, because the Thai
fonts  are  special in heavily using the kerning feature - which means that a non-spacing-marker will have a
negative  kerning and therewith will render into its left pendant - here the spacing character or any preceding
non-spacing-marker.  Without  this  trick  it  wouldn't  be  possible  to  use  the  standard  OS  text routine for
displaying  texts  - which is now used by BareED to allow anti-aliasing text outputs for systems that support it
(mainly, MorphOS and AmigaOS4).

Upon  removing  characters  BareED  will  in  first  place delete the non-spacing-markers - and if there is no
more  a  non-spacing-marker BareED will erase the spacing character. With this behaviour of BareED you're
able to modify characters easily.



@{b}@{fg highlight}There are currently some disadvantages I want to mention here:@{fg text}@{ub}

First  of  all,  the  "Overwriting  mode"  is  out  of order for the time "TIS-620" support is enabled - I shall look
forward enabling it for newer versions of BareED. Currently, I haven't found the time to realize it.

The  line  wrap  mechanism  of  BareED  needs  delimiters  to split up lines into several parts - since the Thai
language  doesn't  use  delimiters  at all it is not possible right now. Dr. Hill is working on an algorithm to make
this  possible. So we are good things for the future that we can provide a useable line wrap mechanism for the
Thai language.

If  you  encounter distorted pixels or false rendered characters click simply on the sizing gadget in the bottom,
right border. BareED is forced by this to re-render the entire page.
If  this happens frequently - and if you are able to reproduce this behaviour - then there is a bug and I would
appreciate if you could send me a bug report.


@endnode


@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

@node issues "Known issues - oh no!"

Disadvantages and mistakes, known to the author

@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}

Cannot   be   used   in   connection  with  Nico  François-PowerSnap-Versions-xx.  This  means  only,  that
PowerSnap  cuts  out not the correct characters to discover, because BareED reserves between every line of
text a separate row.

Marking  a  field  on  a  screen  with  less than 4 colours causes a small problem: Cursor and marked field are
represented in the same colour. Thus you cannot distinguish where the marked field ends.

Blank lines are not represented in the selected marker colour if these are within a marked field.

Only  decimal  numbers  can  be  entered  as  tool  type values: as I already mentioned in the source code of
BareED,  the  functions  provided by my compiler-provider cause a complete computer-crash as for example
"atoi".  Therefore  I  used  the  built-in  OS  function  StrToLong()  the DOS library. This function accepts only
decimal  numbers.  With  the  introduction  of  OS  4.0  this  function could support also dual and hexadecimal
numbers.

Slow  delete / insert from characters: Currently BareED copies and removes every character immediately. This
could  be changed with a line buffer. The problem with a line buffer is that this would have an inflexible size -
the  line,  however,  not,  hmmm.  The  next  problem  is  that the inner cursor of BareED which represents the
visible  cursor  will  not  have  any ground under its feet in this special case. So I do not like to re-work at the
moment the routines.

A  subfunction  added  - that was written in assembler - which reduced drastically the time to displace and to
copy characters.

Pen  selection  not  very friendly: A plan for a future version of BareED is to offer a friendlier interface in order
to choose the pens.

If  you  press  a key and nothing happens, then the system cannot assign any more memory to BareED. In this
special  case  it  is  also not anymore possible to backup that archive onto disk since the "Asl"-file-requester
cannot  be  shown  due  to the low available memory. Perhaps a future version of BareED spends a warning if
you run danger to fall below a lower memory limit.

The  whole  user  interface  of  BareED  is font-sensitive; BareED uses the title font of the screen, this may be
proportional.  If  the  font  is  now  so  big that the window that is computed cannot be opened - basing on the
width  and  height of this font -, BareED will not resort on the font topaz-8 and compute a new window due to
the new scales. The next bug is, that it not spends this mistake.

After  all,  currently  BareED  informs  you  only  about  occurred mistakes that are caused and treated by the
Amiga-DOS.

System  function  ObtainBestPenA()  inconsequent:  First  four  and  last  four  colours  are  used always from
intuition  screens  (MultiColor  mode);  when  ObtainBestPenA() is used, existing colours (pen register) are not
returned  even  if  they  are  the same as the demanded ones. Thus I must do myself my thoughts for the future
how to implement a better relief of sharing screen pens.

Existing  pen  number  are  not  reduced  onto  the  actual,  represent  able  number  of coloured pencils. This
happens  then,  when  you  use  a screen depth of for example 32 colours at the present time and then switch
back to (say) 8 colours.

At  the  moment  BareED  supports  not  more  than 256 pens of a screen, this becomes change in (far) future,
when BareED allows too, to modify the colour-values for the pens.

Created  catalogue,  which  one  was  created with 'CatComp' and where a short cut is invalid for a keyboard
contraction (or twice uses) is not recognized by BareED as such - and thus either does not patch!

Underscorings for short cuts are not set and handled although GadTools 37 could be available.

The  editor-window  can be damaged if a font is supposed to be represented with the connotation 'italic'. This
is  due to the fact that such a font can show a bend to the right side - some fonts even draw also some points
out to the left side!
Currently,  BareED  attempts  calculating  the  needed  room  to the right and left of the drawing area in once,
however, it can fail.

Render  engine  was  written  in  C  ('CHUNKY  TO PLANAR') and with that it is slow. The next one is that this
routine always uses eighth 'bit' deep 'bit-planes' - even if the target area is not so deep.

BareED  is  very  susceptible to mistakes made by third party software. This can result in crashes. Are warned!
Non-appropriate  to  rules  and inconsistently written patches can initiate often BareED to the descend! Since
BareED  works only with the memory that was assigned to him by the system, no third application has the right
to damage memory requested by BareED.
BareED  uses  the  distributed  resources in their full size. The uncontrolled changing only of such a byte can
end in a disaster.

@{fg shine}_______________________________________________________________________________________@{fg shadow}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{fg text}

If  "Line  Wrap"  is  turned  on  and  the  Window-size  was  changed,  any remembered undoing-item will be
declared as invalid and hence no remembered undoing-item can be applied to the text anymore.

Bookmarks, in this special case, would be also invalid but nevertheless not treated as such by BareED.

Starting  with  BareED  0.9963, BareED has got a completely new render engine that allows now anti-aliasing
text  outputs  without  visible drawbacks - mainly, this was necessary for OS4 anti-aliasing feature. As a side
effect,  this means also that AROS and AfA_OS text outputs should work also, but cannot be confirmed by me
because  I don't play with them. I don't know if MorpOS has got such a feature, but if it has, it would now also
benefit from BareED's new render engine.

A  really  hard  drawback by supporting anti-aliasing font rendering is the fact that italic fonts need now twice
as  much time as in previous versions of BareED for drawing the characters onto the screen - and this cannot
be changed!

Mouse  speed  dragging  indicator  may lead characters to be rendered in wrong colours if you switch screen
mode from hi or true colour to LUT (256 colours at most) or vice versa.

Using italic fonts, the visible cursor doesn't take into account the slant and bend factor of this font.

Sometimes,  the  marked area is not entirely shown correctly; especially when a marked block was reduced in
its size (it's annoying but harmless).

If  an  outline  font is not present in the font's root-drawer ("FONTS:") and it should be shown in italic, BareED
cannot calculate the correct slant and bend values.

@endnode

@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

@node limits "Limits of BareED - to be broken..."

Internal limits of BareED:
	Up to 2.1 billions characters per archive
	Up to 2.1 billions pixels per line
	Up to 2.1 billions lines per archive
	Up to 65535 pages per archive
	No screen depth limit
	Any screen size greater than 640 pixels in width and 200 pixels in height
	Up  to 75-pixel height for the font (due to the limit of the visible area; internally BareED can handle fonts
	up to 32767 pixel in height)
	Tabulator  size  up  from 1 to endless (although any tabulator width greater than 2 billions pixels will put
	BareED into trouble)
	Up to 16.7 million different colours per pen supported
	Up to 2.1 billions clipboard units (10 utilized) but currently only one, lonely block supported
	Only one font per text file supported
	Only one font style per text file supported
	Up to 16 plug-ins that can reside at a time in the DAC-menu

@endnode

