@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

@node usage "How do I customize BareED's launch"

BareED  normally  saves  the settings (pens, window dimension and so on) along with the text file that it saves
to  disk  and  then  in the icon (info-file) of this text file, unless you specify "@{fg shine}NoIconSave@{fg text}" in BareED's icon as
tool-type.
When  BareED  loads  in  a  text  file, it checks whether an info-file (icon) for this text file exists - and when it
exists, it will utilize those saved tool-types, e.g. pens.
If  no  info-file exists, BareED runs with the original Workbench settings; by default using a grey background if
you run your Workbench using the pre-defined colours.

My  first  approach  in order to overcome this was by using a default project, what is little more than an empty
text file with a, from BareED's point of view, valid info-file.

BareED  automatically  creates  such  default  projects  in  case  there  is no character in the editor buffer, i.e.
@{fg highlight}amount characters = zero@{fg text}, and you save this empty document to disk.
A  double  click now on this project's icon (info-file) will launch BareED by which BareED is forced to display
the saved settings of this project's info-file.
Unfortunately,  that  would  mean that one has to use the Workbench and the mouse in order to double click a
project's icon. Using the Shell, still a grey background would be displayed.

My current approach is to specify a @{fg shine}default project@{fg text} as @{fg highlight}fall-back project@{fg text}.

You  create  as usual a default project, i.e. you specify the colours, window dimension and so on and save to
disk this empty text file. The text file itself will not be written to disk but the info-file (icon).

Now you enter in BareED's icon:

@{fg shine}FallbackProject=@{fg highlight}"path and name of the default project"@{fg text}

Note that you don't have to append the suffix "@{fg shine}.info@{fg text}" to the name of the default project.

If  you don't like to save along with text files from now on the corresponding info-files but would like to use the
defaulted  settings,  disable  "@{fg shine}NoIconSave@{fg text}"  now,  but  temporarily  enable  it in cases where you are going to
create default projects (@{b}menu: Settings@{ub} -> "@{fg shine}Create Icons?@{fg text}").

Now  a  double click on BareED's icon will launch BareED with the settings you chose in the default project -
and the same applies to launches from the CLI!

Once  more, using a fall-back project instructs BareED to use the defaults you did specify in a default project
when there is no existing icon with tool-types where BareED can take settings from.

In  addition,  a  fall-back  project  is  only  taking  into  account  upon  launching  BareED, it will not be used
anymore  once  BareED is running, i.e. if you load in via the ASL file requester a new document, the currently
used  settings  will  remain valid or, if this document comes with different settings (tool-types set in icon of this
new document), those will be utilized.


Step by step:

Assume the executable BareED is placed in "@{fg shine}Work:tools/editors/BareED/@{fg text}"

Start BareED - either by double clicking its icon or by calling by name out of the CLI.

Choose colours, font, window dimension, screen and tab size.

Save  to  disk  this  empty  document. A requester pops up asking whether to create a default project. Answer
this requester positive.
The ASL file requester is now shown.
Specify the name and the location (path) of this default project and remember both.
Let's assume we've picked "@{fg shine}Work:tools/editors/BareED/default.def@{fg text}"

Now, open BareED's icon in order to edit the tool-types.

Enter a new tool-type and its tool-value:
FallbackProject="@{fg shine}Work:tools/editors/BareED/default.def@{fg text}"

Now go to the CLI (Shell) and enter:

1> work:tools/editors/bareed/bareed

BareED pops up using the defaults you did specify in "@{fg shine}default.defs@{fg text}".


@endnode


@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
@remark +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

@node install "Part Installation"

To  install  BareED  or only parts of this archive, firstly choose the medium and drawer where this install script
should  place  the  files.  Then,  click one or more buttons to let the install script know which parts you want to
have installed. After that, choose "Proceed with Install" to start the installation.

You  can  choose  different mediums and drawers for installation; to do this firstly choose medium/drawer, then
click  one  or  more  "part-buttons",  then  click  "Proceed  with  Install".  Repeat  this  procedure  for different
mediums/drawers.


NOTE:
	An  »ASSIGN«  has  been  made  labelled  "B_Temp:" that points to your »Ram Disk:«. In case you
	want  to  install  BareED only temporarily - without installing BareED for real - then please use the
	»B_Temp:« "volume" instead of "Ram Disk:", this will suppress faults - thank you!


You  have  to  @{"choose the volume (the medium) and the destination drawer" System "Execute GetDestDir"} where you wish to install BareED
and  by BareED used files! You can choose a non-existent drawer, in this case a requester appears - asking
you  if  it  is  okay  to  you  to  create  a  new  drawer;  your  response  to  the appearing requester should be
»Create«. In case your response was not »Cancel«, the new drawer and a desktop image for it will be created!

Which parts of BareED do you like to install?
(Click the buttons that represent the things you want to have installed):

	@{"    " system "Echo >>ENV:temp_cpy_file Copy BareED `GetEnv dest_dir`"}	BareED, the program itself (version 0.9899)
	@{"    " system "Echo >>ENV:temp_cpy_file Copy BareED.info `GetEnv dest_dir`"}	BareED's program pictogram (desktop image; a 4-colour image)

	@{"    " system "Echo >>ENV:temp_cpy_file Copy Button.cfg `GetEnv dest_dir`"}	BareED's configuration file, necessary for BareED's button-bank
	@{"    " system "Echo >>ENV:temp_cpy_file Copy Key.cfg `GetEnv dest_dir`"}	BareED's configuration file, necessary for BareED to support function keys

	@{"    " system "Echo >>ENV:temp_cpy_file Copy Catalogs `GetEnv dest_dir`Catalogs all"}	Catalogue directory with German and French catalogue files

	@{"    " system "Echo >>ENV:temp_cpy_file Copy Knobs `GetEnv dest_dir`Knobs all"}	BareED's default button-bank imagery (standard look)
	@{"    " system "Echo >>ENV:temp_cpy_file Copy Rexx `GetEnv dest_dir`Rexx all "}	BareED's ARexx macro files
	@{"    " system "Echo >>ENV:temp_cpy_file Copy Defs `GetEnv dest_dir`Defs all"}	BareED's alternate icon imagery (4-colour default imagery)
	@{"    " system "Echo >>ENV:temp_cpy_file Copy Tools `GetEnv dest_dir`Tools all"}	Tool directory with the image converter »BitMapSaver«
	@{"    " system "Echo >>ENV:temp_cpy_file Copy Screenshots `GetEnv dest_dir`ScreenShots all"}	Screen shots
	@{"    " system "Echo >>ENV:temp_cpy_file Copy Translation `GetEnv dest_dir`Translation all"}	Files, which can be used as starting-point to translate BareED dependent strings to your native language

	@{"    " system "Echo >>ENV:temp_cpy_file Copy BareED.guide BareED.guide.info LastMinute LastMinute.info `GetEnv dest_dir`"}	The enclosed documentation

	@{"    " system "Echo >>ENV:temp_cpy_file Copy DAC `GetEnv dest_dir`DAC all"}	The complete DAC archive (graphical dump and text highlighting)


	To start the installation, click the button below.
	@{" Proceed with Install" system "run ENV:temp_cpy_file `protect ENV:temp_cpy_file +s`"}

@endnode
